KMO TEST

KMO_test_results = KMO(data_scaled)
cat("KMO Test Result: \n")
## KMO Test Result:
cat("Sample Adequacy: ", KMO_test_results$MSA)
## Sample Adequacy:  0.708387
#nrow(df1_scaled)

FIND CORRELATION OF 33 VARIABLES

data_correlation1 = cor(data_scaled)

BEARTLETT TEST

bartlett_test_result1 = cortest.bartlett(data_correlation1,n=nrow(data_scaled),diag=TRUE)
cat("Bartlett Test Result:\n")
## Bartlett Test Result:
cat("Chi-squared:", bartlett_test_result1$chisq, "\n")
## Chi-squared: 2317.095
cat("P-value:", bartlett_test_result1$p.value, "\n")
## P-value: 8.554242e-222
cat("Degrees of Freedom:", bartlett_test_result1$df, "\n")
## Degrees of Freedom: 528

The test for KMO gives Sample Adequacyis 0.708 > 0.5. .

Further, the Bartlett Test Gives a p-value < 0.05 which suggest the null hypothesis, Ho that the covariances are zero, is rejected.

Both these tests suggests that we can proceed with the factorial analysis.

FACTOR ANALYSIS USING PCA

According to the Parallel Analysis Scree Plots, six factors are suggested. However, these factors only explain about 46% of the cumulative variance. Notably, by increasing the number of factors to 15, around 70% of the variance can be explained.

# Determine the number of factors to extract
fa.parallel(data_scaled, fa = "both", n.iter = 100)

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  6  and the number of components =  6
# we can see that there are 7 eigenvalues of Factor Analysis where the actual data's eigenvalues are larger than the simulated data's eigenvalues.

fa_result <- principal(data_scaled, nfactors=16, rotate="varimax", n.obs=n, scores=TRUE)

factor_names <- paste0("Factor", 1:16)

colnames(fa_result$loadings) <- factor_names
colnames(fa_result$Vaccounted) <- factor_names
colnames(fa_result$scores) <- factor_names

# Print the factor loadings
loadings <- fa_result$loadings
print(loadings)

# Function to create bar plots of loadings
plot_loadings <- function(loadings, factor_num) {
  barplot(loadings, main = paste("Loadings for Factor", factor_num),
          las = 2, cex.names = 0.7, col = ifelse(loadings > 0, "lightblue", "pink"))
}

# Plot loadings for each factor
for (i in 1:ncol(loadings)) {
  plot_loadings(loadings[, i], i)
}

# Function to get top loadings for each factor
get_top_loadings <- function(loadings, n = 5) {
  abs_loadings <- abs(loadings)
  top_n <- order(abs_loadings, decreasing = TRUE)[1:n]
  return(loadings[top_n])
}

# Print top loadings for each factor
for (i in 1:ncol(loadings)) {
  cat("Top loadings for Factor", i, ":\n")
  print(get_top_loadings(loadings[, i]))
}

TOP VARIABLES OF EACH FACTOR

get_top_variables <- function(loadings, n = 3) {
  top_variables <- list()
  for (i in 1:ncol(loadings)) {
    abs_loadings <- abs(loadings[, i])
    top_n <- order(abs_loadings, decreasing = TRUE)[1:n]
    top_vars <- rownames(loadings)[top_n]
    top_variables[[paste0("Factor", i)]] <- top_vars
  }
  return(top_variables)
}

top_vars <- get_top_variables(loadings, n = 3)

# Print top variables for each factor
for (i in 1:length(top_vars)) {
  cat("Top variables for", names(top_vars)[i], ":\n")
  print(top_vars[[i]])
}

PLOT THE DISEASE ACTIVITY AND 15 FACTORS

# Calculate the mean of each factor within each DAS28 activity level
factor_means_activity <- fact_out_combined %>%
  group_by(DAS28_activity) %>%
  summarise(across(starts_with("FACTOR"), mean, na.rm = TRUE))
## Warning: There was 1 warning in `summarise()`.
##  In argument: `across(starts_with("FACTOR"), mean, na.rm = TRUE)`.
##  In group 1: `DAS28_activity = Remission`.
## Caused by warning:
## ! The `...` argument of `across()` is deprecated as of dplyr 1.1.0.
## Supply arguments directly to `.fns` through an anonymous function instead.
## 
##   # Previously
##   across(a:b, mean, na.rm = TRUE)
## 
##   # Now

A CHECK ON CLUSTERING THE FACTORS (KMEDOIDS)

library(RColorBrewer)

data_scaled_with_factor_cores <- cbind(data[,1],data_scaled, factor_scores)

# Select columns for clustering (Factor1 to Factor16)
data_for_clustering <- data_scaled_with_factor_cores[, paste0("Factor", 1:16)]

dist_matrix <- dist(data_for_clustering, method = "euclidean")

# Perform K-Medoids clustering
k <- 2  # Number of clusters
pam_result <- pam(dist_matrix, k = k)


# Print clustering results
print(pam_result)

# Extract cluster membership
cluster_membership <- pam_result$clustering

# Perform PCA for visualization
pca_result <- prcomp(data_for_clustering, scale. = TRUE)  # Scale for PCA

# Create PCA plot colored by clusters
pca_df <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:2])  # Use first two principal components
pca_df$cluster <- factor(cluster_membership)

# Plot using ggplot2
ggplot(pca_df, aes(PC1, PC2, color = cluster)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  labs(title = "K-Medoids Clustering of Factor Data (PCA Plot)",
       x = "Principal Component 1",
       y = "Principal Component 2") +
  theme_minimal()

Here we see that the patients are more or less uniformly distributed in the 2 groups, which cant be clustered using the K-Medoids Clustering.

das28_data <- data[, c("code", "DAS28")]

combined_data_km <- merge(data_scaled_with_factor_cores, das28_data, by = "code")
combined_data_km <- cbind(combined_data_km, cluster = km$cluster)

# Define the labels for points based on DAS28 values
combined_data_km$DAS28_label <- ifelse(combined_data_km$DAS28 < 2.6, "-", "+")

##Graph
ggplot(combined_data_km, aes(x = Factor6, y = Factor9, color = factor(cluster), label = DAS28_label)) +
  geom_text(vjust = -0.5, hjust = 0.5, size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Factors Plot with Clusters and DAS28 Highlighted",
       x = "Factor 6 - Grain Choices and Coffee Consumption Factor",
       y = "Factor 9 - Fish and Oils Factor",
       color = "Cluster") +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Cluster") +
  theme_minimal()

# Calculate percentages for each cluster
percentage_summary <- combined_data_km %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  summarise(DAS28_Remission_percentage = mean(DAS28 < 2.6) * 100,
            DAS28_Active_percentage = mean(DAS28 >= 2.6) * 100)

# Round percentages to 1 decimal place
percentage_summary <- percentage_summary %>%
  mutate(across(starts_with("percent"), ~ round(., 1)))

# Print tabular output
print(percentage_summary)
## # A tibble: 2  3

##     <int>                      <dbl>                   <dbl>
## 1       1                       64.7                    35.3
## 2       2                       60.5                    39.5

Here we see that the patients are more or less uniformly distributed in the groups, which cant be clustered using the K-Means.

FINDING CONFOUNDING FACTORS

conf_indices = c(2, 12, 13, 97:99, 101, 104:105,119,123, 126, 128, 130:132 , 135, 137:143, 145:177, 181:182, 189, 224:226, 229, 124) #Counfounders selected

df_convar <- data.frame(data[,conf_indices])

df_convar[] <- lapply(df_convar, function(x) if(is.character(x)) as.factor(x) else x)

STANDARDIZING 1, 0, TRUE, FALSE FOR DIFFERENT VARIABLES

# Function to convert columns to "VERO" or "FALSO"
convert_to_vero_falso <- function(df, columns) {
  for (col in columns) {
    df[[col]] <- as.character(df[[col]])
    df[[col]][df[[col]] == "1"] <- "VERO"
    df[[col]][df[[col]] == "0"] <- "FALSO"
    df[[col]] <- as.factor(df[[col]])
  }
  return(df)
}

# Define columns to standardize
columns_to_standardize <- c("Past_ETN",
                            "Past_ADA",
                            "Past_GOL",
                            "Past_IFX",
                            "Past_CER",
                            "Past_TCZ",
                            "Past_ABT",
                            "Past_RTX",
                            "Past_Anakinra")

# Apply conversion function
df_convar <- convert_to_vero_falso(df_convar, columns_to_standardize)

# Due to low variation in data for different drugs, we are combining the data to mention any present or past drugs being consumed.

# Columns related to present drugs
present_drugs_columns <- c("Steroids", "Nsaids", "MTX", "SSZ", "LFN", "HCQ", "Gold_Salts", "CYA", "csDMARDS", "bDMARDs", "anti.TNF", 
                           "anti.IL6", "ABT", "RTX", "JAK_inhibitors", "ETN", 
                           "ADA", "GOL", "IFX", "CER", "TCZ", "Partial_Jaki", 
                           "Baricitinib", "Tofacitinib", "Sarilumab")


# Columns related to past drugs
past_drugs_columns <- c("Past_MTX", "Past_SZZ", "Past_LFN", "Past_HCQ", 
                        "Past_GOLD_SALTS", "Past_CYCLOSPORINE", "Past_ETN", 
                        "Past_ADA", "Past_GOL", "Past_IFX", "Past_CER", 
                        "Past_TCZ", "Past_ABT", "Past_RTX", "Past_Sarilumab", 
                        "Past_Anakinra")

# Columns related to disinfectants 
disinfectant_columns <- c("Surface_Disinfectants", "Clothing_Disinfectants", "Fruit_Vegetable_Disinfectants")

# Create present_drugs variable
df_convar$present_drugs <- rowSums(df_convar[, present_drugs_columns] == "VERO") > 0

# Create past_drugs variable
df_convar$past_drugs <- rowSums(df_convar[, past_drugs_columns] == "VERO") > 0

# Create any_disinfectant variable
df_convar$any_disinfectant <- rowSums(df_convar[, disinfectant_columns] == "VERO") > 0

# Convert logical values to "TRUE" or "FALSE" strings
df_convar$present_drugs <- ifelse(df_convar$present_drugs, "TRUE", "FALSE")
df_convar$past_drugs <- ifelse(df_convar$past_drugs, "TRUE", "FALSE")

df_convar$present_drugs <- as.factor(df_convar$present_drugs)
df_convar$past_drugs <- as.factor(df_convar$past_drugs)

df_convar$any_disinfectant <- ifelse(df_convar$any_disinfectant, "TRUE", "FALSE")
df_convar$any_disinfectant <- as.factor(df_convar$any_disinfectant)

df_reg_i$Numbiologicals <- as.factor(df_reg_i$Numbiologicals)

# Categorize RF
df_reg_i$RF <- factor(df_reg_i$RF, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("Negative", "Positive"))

# Categorize BMI
df_reg_i$BMI_Category <- cut(df_reg_i$BMI, 
                             breaks = c(-Inf, 18.5, 24.9, 29.9, Inf), 
                             labels = c("Underweight", "Normal weight", "Overweight", "Obesity"))

# Categorize DAS28 based on the threshold
df_reg_i$DAS28_Category <- ifelse(df_reg_i$DAS28 < 2.6, "Remission", "Active")

# Convert the new categories to factors
df_reg_i$DAS28_Category <- factor(df_reg_i$DAS28_Category, levels = c("Remission", "Active"))

boxplot(df_reg_i$Visit_Age, main = "Box Plot of Visit Age", ylab = "Visit Age")

boxplot(df_reg_i$Disease_Duration, main = "Box Plot of Disease Duration", ylab = "Disease Duration")

median(df_reg_i$Visit_Age)
## [1] 58.46
median(df_reg_i$Disease_Duration)
## [1] 12.81
# Categorize Visit Age and Disease Duration based on their medians.

# Categorize Visit_Age based on the median value
df_reg_i$Visit_Age_Category <- ifelse(df_reg_i$Visit_Age <= 58.46, "Less or Equal to 58.46", "Greater than 58.46")

# Categorize Disease_Duration based on the median value
df_reg_i$Disease_Duration_Category <- ifelse(df_reg_i$Disease_Duration <= 12.81, "Less or Equal to 12.81", "Greater than 12.81")

# Convert the new categories to factors
df_reg_i$Visit_Age_Category <- factor(df_reg_i$Visit_Age_Category, levels = c("Less or Equal to 58.46", "Greater than 58.46"))

df_reg_i$Disease_Duration_Category <- factor(df_reg_i$Disease_Duration_Category, levels = c("Less or Equal to 12.81", "Greater than 12.81"))

APPLYING 16 DIFFERENT REGRESSIONS FOR THE FOOD GROUPS, TAKING 1 INTO ACCOUNT AT ONCE WITH THE LOGISTIC REGRESSION

# List of factors derived from factor analysis
factors <- paste0("Factor", 1:16)

# Prepare the base formula for logistic regression
formula_base <- "DAS28_Category ~ "

# Iterate over each factor
for (factor in factors) {
  # Construct the specific formula for each iteration
  formula <- paste(formula_base, factor)
  
  # Fit the logistic regression model
  model <- glm(formula, data = final_fg_cov_df, family = binomial(link = "logit"))
  
  # Print the summary of the model
  cat("\n\nLogistic Regression Summary for", factor, ":\n")
  print(summary(model))
}

APPLYING LOGISTIC REGRESSION BY CONSIDERING CONFOUNDERS AND 1 FACTOR AT A TIME

# Prepare the base formula for logistic regression
formula_base1 <- "DAS28_Category ~ Energy_kcal + Disease_Duration_Category + Education + Hypertension + TP_CLASSIFICATION + Numbiologicals + Smoker + present_drugs + 
                 past_drugs + any_disinfectant"

# Iterate over each factor
for (factor in factors) {
  # Construct the specific formula for each iteration
  formula <- paste(formula_base1, "+", factor)
  
  # Fit the logistic regression model
  model2 <- glm(formula, data = final_fg_cov_df, family = binomial(link = "logit"))
  
  # Print the summary of the model
  cat("\n\nLogistic Regression Summary for", factor, ":\n")
  print(summary(model2))
}
